-- South African Equities: Anglo, BHP Billiton, Imperial, Mondi, Vodacom Move
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2011-02-02T16:55:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-02/south-african-equities-anglo-bhp-firestone-imperial-mondi.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index climbed the most in five months, rising 649.45, or 2
percent, to 32,487.61 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, surged to the highest level since September 2008,
advancing 16 rand, or 4.5 percent, to 375.50 rand. Copper jumped
to a record $9,988.25 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining company,
gained 9 rand, or 3.2 percent, to 289 rand, the highest since
July 2008.    Firestone Energy Ltd . (FSE SJ), an Australian exploration
company with operations in South Africa, rose the most since
July 12, advancing 6 cents, or 32 percent, to 25 cents.
Firestone Energy said its Sesoko joint venture signed a coal
off-take agreement with Eskom Holdings Ltd. for the power
producer’s Matimba power station.    Imperial Holdings Ltd . (IPL SJ), South Africa’s largest
auto dealer, advanced the most since May 26, jumping 4.20 rand,
or 3.8 percent, to 114.20 rand. Per-share earnings at the
company are expected to have increased between 35 percent and 40
percent and headline earnings per share by as much as 45 percent
in the first-half through December, compared with a year
earlier, Imperial said in a statement after the market closed
yesterday. Imperial was also raised to buy at both Afrifocus
Securities and Avior Research.    Mondi Ltd . (MND SJ),  Europe ’s largest maker of office
paper, climbed 1.50 rand, or 2.6 percent, to 60 rand, the
highest since Oct. 21. Citigroup Inc. analyst Tassin Meyer
upgraded the price estimate on the stock to 70 rand from 63.50
rand.  Pioneer Food Group Ltd. (PFG SJ), a food producer, snapped
five days of losses, increasing 80 cents, or 1.5 percent, to
53.50 rand. The company said in a statement it had withdrawn its
offer to purchase KWV Holdings Ltd.    Vodacom Group Ltd . (VOD SJ), the largest provider of
mobile-phone services to South Africans, rose the most since its
shares started trading in May 2009, jumping 3.22 rand, or 4.5
percent, to 74.50 rand. Vodacom said sales advanced 3.9 percent
to 16 billion rand ($2.24 billion) in the three months through
December, according to a trading update today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
